    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Paycheck Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our free paycheck calculator estimates your net take-home pay based on your annual salary, state tax level, pay frequency, and pre-tax deductions. Enter your gross annual salary and select your state's approximate tax level to instantly see how much you take home each pay period. This is especially useful when evaluating a job offer, planning a budget, or understanding the impact of pre-tax retirement contributions on your paycheck.
      </p>
      <p>
        The calculator uses 2024 federal income tax brackets for a single filer and applies FICA taxes including Social Security and Medicare. Pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions reduce your taxable income before federal and state taxes are calculated, which can meaningfully increase your per-paycheck take-home pay.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Your Paycheck Deductions</h2>
      <p>
        Every paycheck includes several mandatory deductions. Federal income tax is withheld based on the progressive tax bracket system, where higher portions of income are taxed at higher rates. State income tax varies widely; some states like Texas and Florida have no income tax, while others like California can exceed 10%. FICA taxes fund Social Security (6.2% up to the wage base of $168,600 for 2024) and Medicare (1.45% on all income, plus a 0.9% surtax on income above $200,000).
      </p>

      <h3>How Pre-Tax Deductions Save You Money</h3>
      <p>
        Contributing to a 401(k), health insurance, or Health Savings Account (HSA) reduces your taxable income. For example, if you earn $75,000 and contribute $6,000 to a 401(k), your taxable income drops to $69,000. This means you pay less in federal and state income taxes, making the effective cost of that $6,000 contribution significantly less than $6,000 out of pocket. The higher your marginal tax bracket, the greater the tax savings from pre-tax deductions.
      </p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Pay Frequency</h3>
      <p>
        Your pay frequency affects the size of each paycheck but not your annual total. Weekly pay (52 checks) means smaller but more frequent payments, while monthly pay (12 checks) means larger but less frequent deposits. Biweekly pay (26 checks) is the most common in the United States. When budgeting, keep in mind that biweekly pay results in two months per year with three paychecks rather than two, which can be a useful savings opportunity.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How is federal income tax calculated from my paycheck?</h3>
      <p>
        Federal income tax is calculated using a progressive bracket system. Each portion of your taxable income is taxed at increasing rates from 10% to 37%. Your employer withholds an estimated amount each pay period based on your W-4 filing information.
      </p>

      <h3>What is FICA and how much is it?</h3>
      <p>
        FICA stands for the Federal Insurance Contributions Act and includes Social Security tax (6.2% up to $168,600 in 2024) and Medicare tax (1.45% on all wages, plus an additional 0.9% surtax on wages over $200,000). Your employer matches these contributions.
      </p>

      <h3>How do pre-tax deductions affect my paycheck?</h3>
      <p>
        Pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions, health insurance premiums, and HSA contributions reduce your taxable income before federal and state taxes are calculated, effectively lowering your tax bill and increasing your take-home pay relative to the deduction amount.
      </p>

      <h3>Why is my take-home pay less than I expected?</h3>
      <p>
        Your gross pay is reduced by federal income tax, state income tax, Social Security, Medicare, and any pre-tax deductions. Together these typically consume 25-40% of gross pay depending on income level, state, and deductions.
      </p>

      <h3>How does pay frequency affect my paycheck amount?</h3>
      <p>
        Pay frequency determines how many paychecks you receive per year: weekly (52), biweekly (26), semi-monthly (24), or monthly (12). More frequent pay periods mean smaller individual paychecks but the same annual total.
      </p>


